The paper discusses the use of Software Defined Networking (SDN) principles for inter-domain routing and the provision of end-to-end (e2e) network services with Quality of Service (QoS) constraints. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of Control Exchange Points (CXPs) and the need for new business relationships between ISPs, which could fall under the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. The paper also discusses the challenges and benefits of the proposed approach, which could fall under the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) and Information Theory (cs.IT) categories, respectively. Finally, the paper mentions the use of SDN programmability, which could fall under the Software Engineering (cs.SE) category, but this is less likely given the focus on networking and inter-domain routing.
